I have to laugh when I see this.  Notice that the top countries are Benelux and Scandinavian.  When your population is willing to swallow 40-60% income tax rates, your government is more willing to just give the money away.  The US derives ~10% of its GDP (and GNI in turn) from income taxes, whereas those countries on the top of that list derive between 20-40% of the GDP from income taxes.  So those "benevolent" Benelux and Scandinavian governments are giving away the citizens' money that it didn't even have to work to earn.  
<br />

<br />
You will also notice a trend of monotonic decline for the countries meeting or exceeding the UN's desired percentage of 0.7.  Denmark, the Netherlands, Luxembourg and Sweden are all losing ground or simply maintaining their levels because those government <span style="font-weight: bold">spend</span> so much money to affect their GNI and excessive government spending negatively affects economic growth in most cases.  The US's percentage has grown each year even if only by hundredths of a percentage point.  Also the starving people in the Sudan, Sierra Leone, Tanzinia, etc don't care how much money <span style="font-weight: bold">per capita</span> you're giving them, they care how much cold, hard cash flows into their country.  Good intentions and happy percentages don't keep bellies full.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
